{XPPMATH 20 "6#,&*&%\"aG\"\"\")%\"xG\"\"#F&!\"\"*&%\"bGF&F(F&F*" }}}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 2 "  " }
{TEXT 279 58 "What's the famous formula we get when we solve p3=0 for \+
x?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 52 "The famous formula we get is the qu
adratic equation." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 169 "  See if MAPLE know
s a general formula for solving general cubic polynomials, i.e. is the
re a 3rd order formula comparable to the quadratic formula?  If so, ex
hibit it. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 22 "p4:=a*x^3+b*x^2+c*x+d;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p4G,**&%\"aG\"\"\")%\"xG\"\"$F(F(*&%\"bGF()F*\"\"#F(
F(*&%\"cGF(F*F(F(%\"dGF(" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 
"solve(p4=0,x);" }}{PARA 12 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%,(*(\"\"'!\"\"%\"aG
F&,***\"#O\"\"\"%\"bGF+%\"cGF+F'F+F+*(\"$3\"F+%\"dGF+)F'\"\"#F+F&*&\"
\")F+)F,\"\"$F+F&**\"#7F+F6#F+F2,,*(\"\"%F+F'F+)F-F6F+F+*&)F-F2F+)F,F2
F+F&*,\"#=F+F,F+F-F+F'F+F0F+F&*(\"#FF+)F0F2F+F1F+F+*(F<F+F0F+F5F+F+F9F
'F+F+#F+F6F+*,F2F+F6F&,&*(F6F+F'F+F-F+F+*$F@F+F&F+F'F&F(#F&F6F&*(F6F&F
,F+F'F&F&,**(F8F&F'F&F(FGF&**F6F&FIF+F'F&F(FLF+*(F6F&F,F+F'F&F&*(^#F9F
+F6F9,&*(F%F&F'F&F(FGF+*,F2F+F6F&FIF+F'F&F(FLF+F+F+,**(F8F&F'F&F(FGF&*
*F6F&FIF+F'F&F(FLF+*(F6F&F,F+F'F&F&*(^##F&F2F+F6F9FTF+F+" }}}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }{TEXT 280 111 
"Why do you think high school students are never asked to remember the
 general formula for the roots of a cubic?" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 33 "It would be your worst n
ightmare!" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 113 "4.  Solving Equations in O
ne Variable.   There are two different commands to direct Maple to sol
ve an equation:  " }{TEXT 285 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 5 " and " }{TEXT 
286 7 "fsolve." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "They have different pur
poses.  The " }{TEXT 287 5 "solve" }{TEXT -1 63 " command attempts to \+
find exact solutions.  If the expression  " }{TEXT 289 1 "f" }{TEXT 
-1 116 "  is defined in terms of only one variable, there are several \+
different ways to direct Maple to solve the equation  " }{TEXT 290 5 "
f  = " }{TEXT 291 4 "0.  " }{TEXT -1 54 "The following all cause Maple
 to solve the equation   " }{TEXT 292 5 "f  = " }{TEXT 293 2 "0." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 16 "       so
lve(f);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f,x);" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 18 "       solve(f=0);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
20 "       solve(f=0,x);" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 349 "Maple makes an assumption that if the coefficient
s of a polynomial are all given exactly (as integers or rational numbe
rs [ratios of integer]), then you are only interested in finding exact
 solutions.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee that
 the solutions of  a polynomial can be found exactly, only the polynom
ial has solutions.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 78 "You can force Maple to report additional (approximate) \+
solutions by using the " }{TEXT 288 6 "fsolve" }{TEXT -1 76 " command.
  (What does the \"f\" stand for?) ( f stands for floating point.) In
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "addition, to forcing Maple to report
 approximate solutions, you can specify a field extension (typically r
eal or complex) and require Maple to look for solutions which fit in t
hat field extension.  Also, one can specify a range of x values and fo
rce" }{TEXT 296 7 " fsolve" }{TEXT -1 75 " to only look for solutions \+
in that specified range.  For example, compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "fsolve(4*x-x
^3);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6%$!+++++?!\"*$\"\"!F'$\"+++++?F
%" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 23 "fsolve(4*x-x^3,x=1..4)
;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#$\"+++++?!\"*" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT -1 118 "The first one gives a floating point solution fo
r x. The second one asks for solutions that fall between one and four.
" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 28 "For \+
each of the polynomials " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[1]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"\"\"" }
{TEXT -1 9 " through " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "p[14]" "6#&%\"pG6#\"#9" }{TEXT 
-1 19 ", do the following:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "     a.   s
olve for all exact roots whereever possible, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 59 "     b.   find all approximate roots to 10 decimal places
, " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 43 "     c.  factor each into linear fa
ctors.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
106 "You will need to click on  [> in the toolbar to obtain new execut
ion lines just below the cursor position." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "p[1] := x^2-2;" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>&%\"pG6#\"\"\",&*$)%\"xG\"\"#F'F'F,!
\"\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 52 "solve(p[1],x);\nfso
